Project Foundations for Data Science: FoodHub Data Analysis¶

Marks: 60

Context¶

The number of restaurants in New York is increasing day by day. Lots of students and busy professionals rely on those restaurants due to their hectic lifestyles. Online food delivery service is a great option for them. It provides them with good food from their favorite restaurants. A food aggregator company FoodHub offers access to multiple restaurants through a single smartphone app.

The app allows the restaurants to receive a direct online order from a customer. The app assigns a delivery person from the company to pick up the order after it is confirmed by the restaurant. The delivery person then uses the map to reach the restaurant and waits for the food package. Once the food package is handed over to the delivery person, he/she confirms the pick-up in the app and travels to the customer's location to deliver the food. The delivery person confirms the drop-off in the app after delivering the food package to the customer. The customer can rate the order in the app. The food aggregator earns money by collecting a fixed margin of the delivery order from the restaurants.

Objective¶

The food aggregator company has stored the data of the different orders made by the registered customers in their online portal. They want to analyze the data to get a fair idea about the demand of different restaurants which will help them in enhancing their customer experience. Suppose you are hired as a Data Scientist in this company and the Data Science team has shared some of the key questions that need to be answered. Perform the data analysis to find answers to these questions that will help the company to improve the business.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different data related to a food order. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary¶

  • order_id: Unique ID of the order
  • customer_id: ID of the customer who ordered the food
  • restaurant_name: Name of the restaurant
  • cuisine_type: Cuisine ordered by the customer
  • cost: Cost of the order
  • day_of_the_week: Indicates whether the order is placed on a weekday or weekend (The weekday is from Monday to Friday and the weekend is Saturday and Sunday)
  • rating: Rating given by the customer out of 5
  • food_preparation_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the restaurant to prepare the food. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the restaurant's order confirmation and the delivery person's pick-up confirmation.
  • delivery_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the delivery person to deliver the food package. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the delivery person's pick-up confirmation and drop-off information

Question 13: The company wants to provide a promotional offer in the advertisement of the restaurants. The condition to get the offer is that the restaurants must have a rating count of more than 50 and the average rating should be greater than 4. Find the restaurants fulfilling the criteria to get the promotional offer. [3 marks]¶

In [33]:
# This code gets the restaurants with more than 50 rating counts and a rating mean greater than 4.

df_rating = df[df['rating'] != 'Not given'] # make a new df by filtering out the not given ratings.

df_rating['restaurant_name'].count() # Count the total ratings per restaurant. (Successfully taken out the Not given ratings)

vc = df_rating['restaurant_name'].value_counts () # vc is a variable that counts the frequency of ratings per restaurant.

df_requirement_1 = df_rating.loc[df_rating ['restaurant_name'].isin (vc [vc > 50].index)].copy() # Filters the first requirement, which is to have an amount of ratings above 50.

#The following lines converts the column rating values to float, so later the mean can be calculated.
df_requirement_1['rating'] = df_requirement_1['rating'].astype(float)
df_requirement_1['rating'].dtypes # check if it converted to float

#Create a pivot table to get the rating mean per restaurant.
rating_p_table = pd.pivot_table(df_requirement_1, index = ['restaurant_name'], values = ['rating'], aggfunc="mean")
print(rating_p_table)

Question 14: The company charges the restaurant 25% on the orders having cost greater than 20 dollars and 15% on the orders having cost greater than 5 dollars. Find the net revenue generated by the company across all orders. [3 marks]¶

In [34]:
# This code filters the dataframe and calculates the net revenue

# Disregard the orders that have a cost order less or equal to 5 dollars
df_cost_of_the_order = df[df['cost_of_the_order'] > 5] # make a new df by filtering out the prices that are 5 dollars or less.


# Makes a new column based on the condition given, and writes the value of the revenue by multiplyeing the company charges times the cost of the order.
df_cost_of_the_order.loc[df_cost_of_the_order['cost_of_the_order'] > 20, ['revenue']] = df_cost_of_the_order['cost_of_the_order']*0.25
df_cost_of_the_order.loc[df_cost_of_the_order['cost_of_the_order'] <= 20, ['revenue']] = df_cost_of_the_order['cost_of_the_order']*0.15

#Using the sum function on the revenue column will give us the net revenue.
total_revenue = df_cost_of_the_order['revenue'].sum()
#Print the result
print("The revenue generated across all orders was: $" , total_revenue , "dollars")

The revenue generated across all orders was: $ 6166.303 dollars

The net revenue for all the orders so far is $6166.303 dollars

Question 15: The company wants to analyze the total time required to deliver the food. What percentage of orders take more than 60 minutes to get delivered from the time the order is placed? (The food has to be prepared and then delivered.) [2 marks]¶

In [35]:
# This code finds the percentage of the orders that take more than 60 min.
# Sum the times and place the value in a new column: "Total_Time"
df['Total_Time'] = df['food_preparation_time'] + df['delivery_time']

# The following code creates a new column "factor" that will later on help to calculate the percentage.
df.loc[df['Total_Time'] > 60, ['factor']] = df['Total_Time']/df['Total_Time'] # if the total time is higher than 60 it will give a value of 1 on the factor column
df.loc[df['Total_Time'] <= 60, ['factor']] = df['Total_Time']*0  # if the total time is lesser or equal to 60 it will give a value of 0 on the factor column

# Calculating the percentage
orders_above_60 = df['factor'].sum() # Summing up the factors will give the value of the orders that take longer than 60 min.
total_orders = df['factor'].count()  # Counting the total factor column, will give the total value of orders.
percentage_long_orders = orders_above_60 / total_orders * 100  # Calculate the percentage by doing a division and multiplying by 100.

# Print the result
print("The percentage of orders that take longer than 60 min is:", percentage_long_orders ,"%")

The percentage of orders that take longer than 60 min is: 10.537407797681771 %

Observations:¶

10.5% of orders take longer than 60 min. This is not a big significant percentage.

Recommendations:¶

  • My main recommendation is that the company should reach out to other restaurants that are within the most popular cuisines (American, Japanese, Italian and Chinese) and low cost. Since these are the main characteristics the clients are looking for.
  • Another recommendation is that the business should analyze the reason why clients are not rating. The company can send reminders after a few minutes of the client receiving the order, to rate the service. Another strategy is to give a compensation to the client for rating, so that the client has a motive.
  • Since during the weekdays the orders are less, the company can launch a campaign to motivate the clients to also order during weekdays. Also to keep the weekends to have a good service, more delivery workers should work during these days to keep the delivery times low.
  • My last recommendation is to have more information on the customers, for example if the ID is given by the joining on the app. Knowing this information can give better insights for segmentation.
